      <hedline>
        <hl1>Trying Other Ways To Calculate Cab Fares</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dorothy Stearn letter holds Ira Noveck's June 25 letter on how to split cab fares is too complicated; drawing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The writer of ''The Fair Fare When You Share a Taxi'' (June 25), Ira Noveck, must be a money cruncher to come up with such a complicated formula.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The writer of ''The Fair Fare When You Share a Taxi'' (June 25), Ira Noveck, must be a money cruncher to come up with such a complicated formula.</p>
        <p>Most people I know who are the first payers probably overpay out of generosity, but, as in the division of restaurant checks, all things even out eventually. However, if a formula is needed I would suggest that the first payer pay half of the meter plus a greater than usual tip for the driver.</p>
        <p>The writer may want to try again on how to divide the fare when there are four passengers making four stops.</p>
        <p>DOROTHY STEARN  Upper East Side</p>
      </block>
